<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="49" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1394,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,325,1594,1620]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[339,491,1595,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Araeopteron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="makikoae">
<emphasis box="[339,491,1595,1620]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">A. makikoae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguishable from other East Asiatic 
<taxonomicName box="[1034,1181,1595,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Araeopteron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1034,1181,1595,1620]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">Araeopteron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the well marked and patterned, dark grey ground colour; the smoothly rounded dorsal part of valva; the almost equally wide and curving sacculus; lack of an ampulla; the spined, broad patch on the vesica; and the shape of the signum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1394,2023]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1436,152,418]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,349,1754,1780]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">Description.</emphasis>
Adult (
<figureCitation box="[447,566,1754,1780]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[258,1349,203,1785]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,194,1789]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Araeopteron spp., adults. 1, 2: A. amoena, males, Russia, Primorye terr., Gornotayezhnoe; 3, 4: A. fragmenta, Russia, Primorye terr. (3, male, Krounovka; 4, female, Andreevka); 5, 6: A. nebulosa, Russia, Primorye terr., Gornotayezhnoe, males; 7, 8: A. makikoae, Russia, Primorye terr., Gornotayezhnoe (7, male, holotype; 8, male, paratype); 9, 10: A. ussurica, Russia, Primorye terr. (7, male, holotype, Gornotayezhnoe; 8, male, paratype, Zavetnoe); 11: A. koreana, male, holotype, South Korea, Pyoungchanng GW; 12: A. patella, female, holotype, Russia, Primorye terr., Krounovka." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184346/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">
Figs. 
<number box="[517,566,1754,1780]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" value="7.8">7, 8</number>
</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 
<quantity box="[721,855,1754,1780]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 mm</quantity>
. Antennae of both sexes without lamellae, with scales. Labial palps strongly upturned, 
<number box="[625,640,1797,1823]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" value="3.0">3</number>
rd segment 2.5 times as long as 
<number box="[1026,1040,1797,1823]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
nd. Head small, eyes large. Head, patagia, thorax, and ground colour of forewing and hindwing dark grey, forewing suffused with white scales at costal area; both wings with discal spots. All crosslines present, well marked; terminal line on both wings prominently indicated by black interveinal spots. Underside unicolorously grey, without pattern. Colour of abdomen basally and apically grey, medially dark grey. Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[989,1077,1957,1983]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 19" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[157,1436,185,1767]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,185,1774]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 19. Araeopteron spp., male genitalia. 13: A. amoena, S. Korea, prep. 5119 NIAST, Suwon; 14: A. fragmenta, Japan, prep. 4842 O. Karsholt; 15: A. nebulosa, Russia, Primorye, prep. 5745 M. Fibiger; 16: A. makikoae, paratype, Russia, Primorye, prep. 5750 M. Fibiger; 17: A. ussurica Russia, Primorye, prep. 5747 M. Fibiger; 18: A. koreana, South Korea, prep. 5864 M. Fibiger; 19: A. flaccida, South Korea, prep. SJC- 244 - 1 Sohn." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184347/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[1044,1077,1957,1983]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Uncus relatively short, stout, slightly curved; membranous part of valva broadest 
<number box="[771,786,1997,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[795,808,1997,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="49" value="3.0">3</number>
from base, there smoothly rounded; sacculus curved ventrally, almost equally broad throughout, rounded apically; clasper fused to sacculus, ampulla lacking. Aedeagus relatively short and broad; vesica with a spined, broad, sclerotised patch with many small, thin cornuti. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[420,562,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 29" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1807,1831]" captionTargetBox="[177,1436,235,1781]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,194,1783]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 29. Araeopteron spp., female genitalia. 20: A. fragmenta, Japan, prep. 4843 O. Karsholt; 21: A. amoena, South Korea, prep. 5179 NIAST, Suwon; 22: A. patella, paratype, South Korea prep. 5121 NIAST, Suwon; 23: A. nebulosa, Russia, Primorye, prep. 5746 M. Fibiger; 24: A. makikoae, paratype, Russia, Primorye, prep. 5753 M. Fibiger. 25 – 29: Araeopteron spp., structure of signum. 25: A. fragmenta; 26: A. amoena; 27: A. patella; 28: A. nebulosa; 29: A. makikoae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184348/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">
Figs. 
<number box="[486,562,232,258]" pageId="11" pageNumber="50" value="24.29">24, 29</number>
</figureCitation>
). Antrum triangular, laterally with long posterior extensions; ductus bursae relatively short and narrow, membranous; posterior part of corpus bursae cylindric, anterior part ovoid, with broad shuttlecock-shaped signum, having broad convexity with small opposite directed spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
